            <p class="text-white/90 text-sm leading-relaxed">Client seeking architect for $2.4M custom home visits 12 architect portfolios. 10 have basic grids of project photos, click to enlarge, that's it. 2 modern sites with full-screen project galleries, before/after sliders, client testimonials woven into case studies, smooth transitions, narratives explaining design decisions. Both architects do excellent work. Which 2 get the call? For architects, portfolio presentation = perceived quality. Your best photos in a basic grid = filing cabinet, not experience. Clients hire architects who can sell their vision. Your website is your first sales meeting. Design the presentation like you design buildings.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MY EXPERIENCE: ARCHITECT PORTFOLIO CASE STUDY -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 to-amber-50">
    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-4xl">
      <div class="bg-white border-[3px] border-orange-300 p-8 md:p-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">My Experience With Architects</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-8 uppercase tracking-wider font-black">Real results from real architecture practices</p>

        <div class="bg-orange-100 border-l-[3px] border-orange-700 pl-6 py-5 rounded-r mb-6">
          <p class="text-sm font-black text-orange-800 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE BEFORE (March 2023)</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Marcus Chen, independent architect in Seattle (2023). Basic WordPress site: logo, "About" page (AIA certification, 15 years experience, degrees), "Projects" page (grid of 24 thumbnail photos, click for larger image, no descriptions), "Contact" form. Stunning projects (4 award-winning residential designs), invisible presentation. Monthly project inquiries: 8-12. Phone calls: 20/month asking "process?" "timeline?" "fees?" (all answerable on site). Client showing portfolio to spouse: "The work looks good, but the website feels basic. Are they professional?" Monthly revenue: $48,000 (1-2 projects/month, $40-60K avg). Competitors with modern portfolios booking 3-4 projects/month. Marcus doing better work, earning less.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-orange-100 border-l-[3px] border-orange-700 pl-6 py-5 rounded-r mb-6">
          <p class="text-sm font-black text-orange-800 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE FIX (May 2023)</p>
          <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Built Framer site: full-screen project galleries with smooth transitions (each project tells a story), before/after sliders showing transformations (original 1980s builder-grade → Marcus's modern redesign), client testimonials woven into case studies ("Marcus listened to how we LIVE, not just what we wanted"), detailed project narratives (design decisions, material choices, sustainability features), transparent process page (discovery → schematic design → design development → construction docs → construction administration with typical timelines), services clearly listed (residential, additions, remodels, feasibility studies), fees range ($150-250/hour, 10-15% construction cost). Compressed all 3MB photos to 200KB, lazy loading. Launched May 20, 2023. Build time: 3 days. Cost: $25/month Framer. No developer needed.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-orange-100 border-l-[3px] border-orange-700 pl-6 py-5 rounded-r mb-6">
          <p class="text-sm font-black text-orange-800 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">THE AFTER (January 2024 - 8 Months Later)</p>
